hands_on_practices.problem:
A materials scientist is studying a simplified one-dimensional model for an electron trapped in a quantum structure of length $L$. In this model, the spatial component of the electron's wavefunction, denoted by $\psi(x)$, is assumed to be constant over the first half of the structure and zero everywhere else. Specifically, the wavefunction is given by the piecewise function:
$$
\psi(x) = \begin{cases} 
C & \text{for } 0 \le x \le L/2 \\
0 & \text{otherwise} 
\end{cases}
$$
Here, $C$ is a real, positive constant representing the amplitude of the wavefunction, and $L$ is the length of the structure. For this wavefunction to be physically meaningful, it must be normalized. Determine the value of the constant $C$ that satisfies the normalization condition. Express your answer as a symbolic expression in terms of $L$.
